  <span id="freeText3288915311546780963" style="display:none">Is February too early to say that this is and will be the best book I read all year? Regardless, <u>Godric</u> was a wonderful surprise. I had read one other book by Frederick Buechner (<u>Telling the Truth: The Gospel as Tragedy, Comedy, and Fairy Tale</u>) and enjoyed that one very much. However, this book is on a completely different level.<br /><br />Buechner somehow melded Augustine's <u>Confessions</u> with <u>Gargantua and Pantagruel</u> by Francois Rabelais. The story is a tragicomic tale of a twelfth century Englishman who, all too aware of his sinful nature, recounts his life from childhood until his last days to a fellow monk whom he despises. Sprinkled in are ridiculous characters, slightly lewd humor (but written so well that you can't help but enjoy it), disturbing introspections, and a pining for redemption. The fact that Buechner is actually a Presbyterian minister makes the story all the more quirky and lovable in my opinion. More importantly, I did not find this book preachy. It would have been an easy corruption to turn a fictional story about a pseudo-saint into a prolonged sermon told by a fictional character. Godric instead retells his life with all of its transgressions mixed with wandering mixed with righteousness mixed with Providence. In fact, in opposition to a preachy tone, Godric is a man of the earth. Constantly depicted as dirty, frazzled, and odorous, he is firmly rooted in the human condition yet strives to raise his eyes to God. <br /><br />Buechner himself: "From old Godric I learned much about how to bear loss, great pain, and about faith in the face of despair and something like joy in the midst of great sadness and anxiety."<br /><br />It's interesting to note that <u>Godric</u> was a runner up for the Pulitzer Prize to <u>Confederacy of Dunces</u> by John Kennedy Toole which is another book I cherish.</span>
