  <span id="freeText14692274782458312836" style="display:none">I'm really glad I read this deep, deep character study. I did find myself liking, and respecting, the person Godric (the fictional character, not the historical person, of which we know a little) less and less as the book progressed. He's actually quite capable of doing some unsavory things.<br /><br />That is, however, the theme of the book. How an ordinary sinner becomes a Saint. The book is not exactly cynical, but it is extremely unsentimental, and that might be a problem for some readers. It's not just about the dirty underside of a saint's life, however. When we're given the explanation of Godric's healing of a leper, for example, we find the healing kiss was given almost by accident. From Godric's perspective, the incident had no aura of blessing or grace at all, and he finds the reverence he receives grotesque. But the point is that the miracle is pure grace from God, and that God's grace works among, and even in, our failings and limitations, in ways subtle and incomprehensible.<br /><br />Which strikes me as a completely correct way to dramatize grace.<br /><br />One thing more: readers will intuit the "poetry" of the prose. In fact, I eventually wised up to the author's use of iambic meter almost all the time. Once I noticed it, I found it hard to unsee, and that's ... not ideal. Some sentences, with their odd word choices, tha-dump along and almost approach doggerel. But other readers with minds more open to poetry, and poetry-prose chimeras, will probably love those iambs.</span>
